                    <physDesc>
                        <objectDesc>
                            <supportDesc>
                                <support>
                                    <p>Large fragment of thick plaque of hard brown/grey limestone, all sides broken and heavily abraded. Face is polished. Rear has deep, but intentional, step cut out of right hand side (thus stone is deeper on left hand side). More of the stone was preserved below when it was first seen in the early 1600s.</p>
                                    <material ana="#material.stone.limestone" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/material/lod/66.html">limestone</material>
                                    <objectType ana="#object.plaque" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/objtyp/lod/259">plaque</objectType>
                                    <dimensions>
                                        <height unit="cm">26.5</height>
                                        <width unit="cm">43</width>
                                        <depth unit="cm">16 (with protrusion), 9.5 (without)</depth>
                                    </dimensions>
                                </support>
                                <condition/>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>
                                    <p>Only two lines of Latin text are preserved (two more below were previously observed). There is a large vacat (at least 47mm) above line 1, so it seems likely that there is no missing text above. Neat comma-shaped interpunct line 2.</p>
                                    <rs ana="#execution.chiselled" ref="http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1">chiselled</rs>
                                    <damage/>
                                </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>
                                <p>Monumental letters, very straight and neatly carved, almost without serifs. Letters are widely spaced.</p>
